The term ''Capoid'' was introduced as a racial category uniting the Khoikhoi and San peoples as separate from other sub-Saharan populations was proposed by [[Carleton S. Coon]] (1962). It is  named for the [[Cape of Good Hope]].<ref name="ReferenceA">''[[The Origin of Races]]'' (1962).
Moore, Ruth ''Evolution'' (Life Nature Library) New York:1962 Time, Inc. Chapter 8: "The Emergence of Modern ''Homo sapiens''" Page 173--First page of picture section "Man and His Genes": The ''Capoid'' race is identified as one of the five major races of mankind, along with the ''[[Mongoloid race|Mongoloid]]'', ''[[Congoid]]'', ''[[Caucasoid race|Caucasoid]]'', and ''[[Australoid]]'' races (pictures of a person typical of each race are shown)</ref> Coon (1962) proposed that the term "[[Negroid]]" should be abandoned, and the sub-Saharan African populations of West African stock (including the [[Bantu people|Bantu]]) should be termed "[[Congoid]]" instead.<ref name="ReferenceA"/> Cavalli-Sforza at al. (1994) used the term ''Khoisanid'' instead of Coon's "Capoid".<ref>[[Luigi Luca Cavalli-Sforza|Cavalli-Sforza, L. Luca]]; Menozzi, Paolo; and Piazza Alberto ''The History and Geography of Human Genes'' Princeton, New Jersey: 1994 Princeton University Press "Khoisanids" pp. 174–177</ref> The observation of a significant difference between  the Khoisan and the populations of [[Congoid|West African]] stock was not original to Coon, it had been noted as early as 1684 [[François Bernier]], the early modern author who originally introduced the French word ''race'' to refer to the large divisions of mankind. Bernier outside of five large divisions described in more detail proposes the  possible addition of more categories, primarily for  "the Blacks of the Cape of Good Hope" (''les Noirs du Cap de bonne Esperance''), which seemed to him to be of significantly different build from most other populations below the Sahara.<ref>Anonymous [F. Bernier], [http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k56535g/f135.item "Nouvelle division de la terre par les différentes espèces ou races qui l'habitent"], ''Journal des Sçavants'', 24 April 1684, [[:File:Nouvelle division de la terre, par les différentes espèces ou races d'homme qui l'habitent.png|p. 133]]&ndash;140. '' les  Noirs du Cap de bonne Esperance semblent estre d'une autre espece que ceux du reste de l'Afrique. '' (p. 136). See also Charles Frankel, ''La science face au racisme'' (1986), [https://books.google.ch/books?id=szfsLo3VSVAC&pg=PA41  41f.]</ref>

